    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-04-02T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-04-02T20:00:00-05:00" n="365"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                <head>365. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Arab Republic</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d365fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, RG 59, Central Files 1964-66, <gloss target="#t_POL1"
                            >POL</gloss> 32-1 SAUD-YEMEN. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_JCF1">Jones</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MGC1"
                            >Moore</persName>, cleared by <persName corresp="#p_DRP1"
                            >Davies</persName>, and approved by <persName corresp="#p_JJD2"
                            >Jernegan</persName>. Repeated to Jidda and Taiz.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-04-02T20:00:00-05:00">April 2, 1965, 8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6051. Saudi-Yemen Border. We are gratified by indications (Cairo’s 3439<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d365fn2">In telegram 3439 from Cairo, April 1, Battle reported
                        that in response to his expression of U.S. concern over any extension of
                            <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> military activities to Saudi
                        airspace or territory, Deputy Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_FM5"
                            >Fawzi</persName> assured him that the United Arab Republic would
                        exercise all restraint possible. (Ibid., <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss>
                        27 YEMEN)</note> and 3448<note n="3" xml:id="d365fn3">Dated April 1.
                        (Ibid.)</note>) <gloss target="#t_UARG1">UARG</gloss> taking pains to avoid
                    violation of Saudi territory. However, Jidda’s 740 and 744<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d365fn4">Both dated April 1. (Ibid., and <gloss target="#t_POL1"
                            >POL</gloss> 31-1 SAUD-<gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>)</note>
                    report two recent instances where <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>
                    precautions broke down. Hope Embassy (perhaps Political Counselor to Al-Khouli)
                    will have early opportunity insure <gloss target="#t_UARG1">UARG</gloss>
                    understands <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> concerned over any violations
                        <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> territory or airspace and <gloss
                        target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> commitment to support Saudi safety and security
                    remains in effect. We trust reports of massive Egyptian troop movements in
                    border area do not foreshadow increased border friction.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
